Task 1

library(jsonlite)

The following code reads the JSON file into R.

## Read JSON file into R
## fromJSON() function converts JSON data to R objects
temp <- fromJSON(readLines("/course/COVID/JSON/owid-covid-data.json"))
## Warning in readLines("/course/COVID/JSON/owid-covid-data.json"): incomplete
## final line found on '/course/COVID/JSON/owid-covid-data.json'
## The temp is list and has lists within (the nested list).
class(temp)
## [1] "list"
length(temp)
## [1] 211

Commentary:

The JSON file contains information for 211 locations (the last one is for the entire World), including numbers of cases of COVID per day (from the start of the year). We are interested in the relationship between the stringency of measures (against COVID) and the number of cases per day. Thus, we need to extract new_cases_per_million and stringency_index data from the JSON file.

There are 211 records in total, but the last one is the record for the entire World (we need to remove OWID_WRL). I found that not all countries have both new_cases_per_million and stringency_index. Thus, we need records that have both variables in it (i.e., need to remove non-paired ones).

new_cases_per_million <- numeric(0)
stringency_index <- numeric(0)


for (i in 1:(length(temp)-1)){ ## only keep the paired ones
  if(length(temp[[i]]$data$new_cases_per_million) == length(temp[[i]]$data$stringency_index)){
  new_cases_per_million <- c(new_cases_per_million, temp[[i]]$data$new_cases_per_million)
  stringency_index <- c(stringency_index, temp[[i]]$data$stringency_index)
  }
}

## Create a data frame
cases <- data.frame(new_cases_per_million, stringency_index)
## Have a look at the dimension of the data frame
dim(cases)
## [1] 32927     2

Task 2

library(mongolite)

The file “COVID” contained in the MongoDB database (A document-oriented database based on JSON documents). The following code reads the file into R.

## Connect via m <- mongo(...)
m <- mongo("COVID")
## We use queries via a find operation that uses documents to specify selections:
## 1) Need to extract the two variables of interest from the databases;
## 2) Need to exclude the World record.
temp2 <- m$find(query='{"location": {"$ne": "World"}}', fields='{"data.new_cases_per_million": 1, "data.stringency_index": 1, "_id": 0}')
## I found that not all countries have both `new_cases_per_million` and `stringency_index`
## Thus, we need records which have both variables in it (i.e. need to remove non-paired ones)
new_cases_per_million <- numeric(0)
stringency_index <- numeric(0)

for (i in 1:(dim(temp2)[1])){ ## only keep the paired ones
    if(length(data.frame(temp2[i,1])$new_cases_per_million) == length(data.frame(temp2[i,1])$stringency_index)){
      new_cases_per_million <- c(new_cases_per_million, data.frame(temp2[i,1])$new_cases_per_million)
      stringency_index <- c(stringency_index, data.frame(temp2[i,1])$stringency_index)
    }
} 

## Create a data frame
cases.2 <- data.frame(new_cases_per_million, stringency_index)

Extract the date and the number of cases for Afghanistan from the XML file:

## Extract elements of interest using xml_find_all() and XPath expressions
record <- xml_find_all(temp3, "//record[countriesAndTerritories/text()='Afghanistan']")
date <- xml_text(xml_find_all(record,".//dateRep/text()"))
cases_af <- xml_text(xml_find_all(record,".//cases/text()"))

## Combine the 2 variables into a single data frame.

## Specify the variables as the appropriate class.
AF.df$date <- as.Date(AF.df$date, format = "%d/%m/%Y")
AF.df$cases <- as.numeric(AF.df$cases_af)

Commentary:

There are \(14\) negative values in new_cases_per_million. Also, there are \(458\) missing values (NA).

The number of negative values accounts for a small fraction of the data and would not harm our analysis if we drop them. Thus we choose only to keep those positive numbers of cases:

plot(density(cases$new_cases_per_million, na.rm = TRUE), main="Distribution of 'new_cases_per_million'")

Commentary:

A plot of the new_cases_per_million distribution looks very skewed. Thus we consider to transform it by using squra root transformation or log transformation.

There is an increasing trend between the log of new cases per million and the stringency index, but after the index hit 60, the number of new cases seems to be flattened out (the rate of increase slows down).

plot(x = df$stringency_index, y=df$log_case, pch = 19, col = grey(0, 0.1), xlab = "Stringency Index", ylab = "log(new_cases_per_million)")

Modelling

## Define 10 splits
set.seed(123)
labels <- rep(1:10, length.out=N)
groups <- sample(labels)
RMSE <- function(i, formula) {
    testSet <- groups == i
    trainSet <- groups != i
    fit <- lm(formula, data.frame(x=df$stringency_index[trainSet], y=df$log_cases[trainSet]))
    pred <- predict(fit, data.frame(x=df$stringency_index[testSet]))
    ob <- df$log_cases[testSet]
    sqrt(mean((pred - ob)^2))
}

Commentary:

The RMSE() function splits the data into test and training sets using a label between 1 and 10.

  • Step 1: It then uses the training set to fit a model relating the number of cases per day (we use the log of new cases per million) to the stringency of measures (against COVID) based on the provided formula;

  • Step 2: It generates predictions for the test set;

  • Step 3: It calculates the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) for the test set.

The following code evaluates the constant cases (per million) per day model by cross-validation using the formula \(y ~ 1\).

mean(sapply(1:10, RMSE, y ~ 1))
## [1] 2.248936

The following code evaluates a simple linear regression model using the formula \(y ~ x\). We perform cross-validation by calling RMSE() for i from 1 to 10, then average the resulting the RMSE values.

mean(sapply(1:10, RMSE, y ~ x))
## [1] 2.179995

The following code evaluates a polynomial regression model using the formula \(y ~ x + I(x^2)\). We perform cross-validation by calling RMSE() for i from 1 to 10, then average the resulting the RMSE values. The polynomial regression model gives the smallest RMSE.

mean(sapply(1:10, RMSE, y ~ x + I(x^2)))
## [1] 2.157435

A plot of the complete data shows the polynomial regression model performs better than the simple linear regression model and the overall mean of cases per day; the polynomial regression model allows for the change of increasing rate when the index hit 60.

PredSimple <- mean(df$log_cases)
Fit1 <- lm(log_cases ~ stringency_index, data = df)
Fit2 <- lm(log_cases ~ stringency_index + I(stringency_index^2), data = df)
o <- order(df$stringency_index)

plot(df$log_case~df$stringency_index, pch = 19, col = grey(0, 0.1), xlab = "Stringency Index", ylab = "log(new_cases_per_million)")
abline(h=PredSimple, col="grey", lwd=3)
lines(df$stringency_index[o], fitted(Fit1)[o], col="blue", lwd=3)
lines(df$stringency_index[o], fitted(Fit2)[o], col="red", lwd=3, type = "l")

Conclusion

  • The data consist of information for 211 locations (the last one is for the entire World), including numbers of cases of COVID per day (from the start of the year). We are interested in the relationship between the stringency of measures (against COVID) and the number of cases per day. We extracted the two interested variables from the file and ended up with 32,927 records. We found that there is an increasing trend between the log of new cases per million and the stringency index, but after the index hit 60, the number of new cases seems to be flattened out (the rate of increase slows down).

  • One reason for caution is that we throw out about \(1/3\) of our data which are zero values, so our estimate of the zero cases would be less reliable.

  • We used 10-fold cross-validation to determine that the polynomial regression model performs better than the simple linear regression model and the overall mean of cases per day.
